Stable priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the fallout of COVID-19.
However, the world's most "fragile" states face a particularly complex set of problems.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and a dysfunctional public administration.
Today, these elements leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to navigate the pandemic is precisely what fragile states are lacking: a functioning state apparatus capable of developing and implementing action plans, an effective police force to enforce the rules, social programs that provide funding, supplies, and healthcare services to treat those infected.
The lack of resources of the state is immediately felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions of Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also involves confidence in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states hardly benefits from the approval of the population.
In countries recovering from a conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will hesitate to support the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an indispensable component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to help those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not present enough to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would evade the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the weight of young demographics and geographical distance.
However, from our perspective as co-chairs of the new Council on State Fragility, it is clear that was not the case.
In the past few weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries that were hit by the coronavirus first.
Even worse, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more significant for fragile states. They will not be the result of national lockdowns alone, but also of what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has faltered, expatriate remittances have plummeted, basic product prices and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are piling up.
Since fragile states rely heavily on imports for most of their food, we are increasingly talking about "hunger" and even "famine".
We should now understand that the problems of poorer countries have become, for the most part, global issues, whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal organizations, or terrorism, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the impoverished populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will only worsen.
That's why the Council on State Fragility has made it its top priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must face.
The council, composed of former global leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, and development organization presidents, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its purpose will be to guide national and international policymakers on how fragile states will navigate this crisis and tackle their broader, deeper problems.
Decentralisation, adaptability, and wise use of data will be essentials.
For example, it is widely proven that 'targeted lockdowns' of local outbreaks are often more suitable than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West reaches its end and the sense of urgency fades.
We are offering five recommendations.
First and foremost, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will be synonymous with universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telephone networks should be utilized to collect information on immediate needs and disbursed regular, albeit short-term, benefits.
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which cultivated rice, has become increasingly dependent over the past few decades.
In general, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Local initiatives for the production of staple crops must be quickly rolled out to a significantly wider scale.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production is launched, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When a threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, fragile states need immediate business assistance.
As financial institutions most involved in international development are aware, countries with lower-income economies often neglect small businesses and suffer the negative consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
However, it is precisely these small businesses that need larger investments.
Ultimately, the G20 should do more to support the heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral aid for development will repay approximately $40 billion to private and public creditors this year alone.
In order to prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend accumulated debt not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
In addition, it is crucial that all fragile states receive emergency funding to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions – including countries that do not normally have access to World Bank or International Monetary Fund financing.
COVID-19 will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we can mitigate the worst effects of the pandemic.
If there's one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it's that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
